Here's the complete migration from ASP.NET Web Forms to ASP.NET Core 8 MVC/API.

## What's wrong with the original code

All three patterns rely on `Thread.Abort`, which throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+:

| Old API | Hidden behavior |
|---------|----------------|
| `Response.End()` | Calls `Thread.Abort` to stop execution |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | The `true` (endResponse) calls `Thread.Abort` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Swallows the abort â€” no longer thrown |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;
using System.Text;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    // POST /Report/Export
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();

        // Return a FileResult â€” no Response.Clear/Write/End needed.
        // The framework handles Content-Disposition and streaming.
        return File(
            Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data),
            "text/csv",
            "report.csv");
    }

    // POST /Report/Redirect
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult RedirectAction()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            // Just return a redirect result â€” no Thread.Abort, no endResponse.
            return Redirect("/login");
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // No catch (ThreadAbortException) â€” it's gone entirely.
        // OperationCanceledException replaces it for request-aborted scenarios.
        catch (OperationCanceledException)
        {
            // Client disconnected mid-request â€” nothing to redirect to.
            return StatusCode(499); // client closed request
        }
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }

    private string GenerateReport() => /* ... */ "";
    private void ProcessRequest() { /* ... */ }
    private void LogError(Exception ex) { /* ... */ }
}
```

## Key changes explained

### 1. `Response.End()` â†’ just return
ASP.NET Core actions control flow by **returning an `IActionResult`**. There's nothing to "end" â€” once you return, the framework writes the response and completes the request. `File()` handles `Content-Type`, `Content-Disposition`, and streaming in one call.

### 2. `Response.Redirect(url, true)` â†’ `return Redirect(url)`
The `true` parameter existed solely to abort the thread after queuing the redirect. In ASP.NET Core, `return Redirect(url)` exits the action method naturally â€” no abort needed.

### 3. `catch (ThreadAbortException)` â†’ remove or replace with `OperationCanceledException`
`ThreadAbortException` is **never thrown** in modern .NET. If you need to detect a cancelled request (client disconnect), check `HttpContext.RequestAborted` or catch `OperationCanceledException`.

## Passing cancellation through long-running work

If `ProcessRequest()` does heavy I/O or computation, wire up `HttpContext.RequestAborted`:

```csharp
[HttpPost]
public async Task<IActionResult> RedirectAction(CancellationToken cancellationToken)
{
    // ASP.NET Core automatically binds this to HttpContext.RequestAborted
    try
    {
        await ProcessRequestAsync(cancellationToken);
        return Redirect("/success");
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cancellationToken.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        return StatusCode(499);
    }
    catch (Exception ex)
    {
        LogError(ex);
        return Redirect("/error");
    }
}
```

## Common pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|---------------|
| Keeping `Response.End()` calls | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` at runtime â€” not a compile error |
| Calling `Response.Redirect()` without returning | Code after the redirect **keeps executing** â€” there's no abort to stop it. Always `return Redirect()`. |
| Swallowing `OperationCanceledException` silently | Let it propagate unless you have explicit recovery logic. Swallowing it masks client disconnects. |
| Forgetting `?.` on `User.Identity` | `Identity` can be `null` in ASP.NET Core if no auth middleware is configured |
| Writing to `Response.Body` then redirecting | Unlike Web Forms, you can't mix response writes and redirects â€” the response is already started. Pick one. |
| Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource` | If you create your own `CancellationTokenSource` (e.g., for timeouts), wrap it in `using`. The framework-provided `CancellationToken` parameter is managed for you. |
